J. B. Rainsberger wrote:

&gt;Mark Levison wrote:
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;In NUnit/.NET land we had test FixtureSetup/FixtureTearDown (run once for
&gt;&gt;each test fixture, not once a test case) in addition to regular setUp and
&gt;&gt;tearDown. I&#39;ve tended to use these methods when I want to do something
&gt;&gt;expensive (File I/O etc.). While I know I should avoid expensive operations
&gt;&gt;in my test cases sometimes they are very useful. So is there are a standard
&gt;&gt;idiom for doing fixture setup? Do I resort to statics?
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;Yes. Use TestSetup to set them up:
&gt;
&gt;     public static Test suite() {
&gt;         return new TestSetup(new TestSuite(MyClass.class)) {
&gt;             // override setUp()
&gt;             // override tearDown()
&gt;         };
&gt;     }
&gt;  
&gt;
Or use JUnit 4:

public class MyClass {
    @BeforeClass public static void fixtureSetup() {
       // performed once for the whole class
    }

    @BeforeClass public static void moreFixtureSetup() {
       // performed once for the whole class
    }

    @AfterClass public static void fixtureTeardown() {
       // performed once for the whole class
    }
}

Cheers,

    David Saff
